Two stones in the table carry the same D-VS1 grade at 5ct: the [5.00ct at $121,475](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/16360919?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and the [5.09ct at $251,745](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/18249190?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). The price difference at the same color and clarity grade is $130,270. This is how natural 5ct pricing works — diamonds are priced on individual stone characteristics beyond the certificate: fluorescence, polish, symmetry, and exactly how the specific inclusions sit within the 12mm × 9mm table.

At 5ct, you do not buy a grade category. You buy one specific stone with its own set of characteristics. Always request the full GIA grading report and a 360° video for every natural 5ct stone you consider at these prices — the certificate and the visual reality can tell very different stories.

---

> "When someone comes to me for a natural 5ct emerald cut, the first thing I do is slow them down. There are six certified stones in the current market and a $130,000 spread between D-VS1 and D-VS1. Same grade, different stones, completely different prices. At this level you are not buying a category — you are buying that stone specifically, and you need to know exactly why it costs what it does."
>
> — Farzana, DiamondCritics

