The E-VVS1 IGI stones at $8,210–$8,339 are the entry point and the most popular choice for buyers who want a 5ct emerald cut ring for under $10,000 complete. E color is near-colorless and VVS1 is a better clarity grade than the cheapest natural 5ct stone in the market at $121,475 (which is VS1). Add a [$860 solitaire setting](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/ten-prong-solitaire-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-by-james-allen-item-311235?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and the complete 5ct ring is $9,070–$9,199.

The D-VVS1 stones at $9,491–$11,732 step up to D color while maintaining VVS1 clarity. D color means the stone is colorless — the highest grade on the color scale — and VVS1 means inclusions are not visible even under 10× magnification. For buyers who want the top color grade at 5ct lab and prefer a complete ring under $13,000, the [$9,491 IGI D-VVS1](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29038935?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) plus the [$1,200 platinum solitaire](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/ten-prong-solitaire-engagement-ring-in-platinum-by-james-allen-item-311240?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) totals $10,691. D-VVS1 in a natural 5ct stone would cost well over $200,000 for the stone alone.

