## The Six-Figure Wall

Natural 5ct emerald cut diamonds cost six figures because of three compounding factors that all hit simultaneously at this weight.

First: exponential carat pricing. In natural diamonds, price per carat increases as weight increases. A 1ct emerald cut might cost $5,000 per carat — a 5ct costs $24,000 to $50,000 per carat, plus the rarity premium for finding a single stone at this weight with acceptable grades.

Second: the step-cut clarity premium. The emerald cut's wide, open table shows inclusions that brilliant cuts hide. At 5ct and 12mm × 9mm, VS1 clarity is the minimum for a stone that looks correct — D color and VS1 are both required, which is exactly what the natural benchmark at $121,475 carries.

Third: natural rarity at size. Only six GIA-certified natural emerald cut diamonds at 5ct exist in current certified market inventory, ranging from $121,475 to $251,745. When supply is this thin, each stone prices individually on its specific characteristics — which is why two D-VS1 stones at 5ct can differ by $130,000.

[![Emerald cut diamond engagement ring rose gold with edge halo detail](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/BrioPackshotBox/Rings/505132/505132_M1_EMR_DIM_wht_0100CT_R_Box4_004_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?MetalType=all&Diamonds=Dia&ShapeID=Emerald&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

In lab, all three factors disappear. Lab production scales with demand, carat weight does not carry an exponential rarity premium, and clarity at 5ct is available at D-FL for under $20,000. The six-figure wall exists only in natural diamonds — it is not a property of the shape or size, it is a property of earth's supply.

---

## What to Check Before Buying a 5 Carat Emerald Cut Diamond Ring

At $9,070 for lab or $126,000+ for natural, five things deserve careful review before you commit.

**Exact dimensions.** Confirm the millimeter measurements, not just the carat weight. "5ct emerald cut" describes 12mm × 9mm only on average — individual stones can run 11.5mm × 9.5mm or 12.5mm × 8.5mm at the same weight. Both are 5ct; both look different on the hand. The L/W ratio should fall between 1.28 and 1.35 for the classic emerald cut proportion. Outside that range is a style preference — make sure you know what you are buying.

**Depth percentage.** For any emerald cut, 60–70% depth is the standard range. Below 60%, the stone looks flat and the hall-of-mirrors effect collapses — the layers of rectangular reflections require sufficient depth to develop. Above 72%, the stone looks dark face-up. At 5ct, a stone that fails on depth percentage will look wrong at every viewing angle.

**Corner integrity.** The emerald cut's four corners are its most vulnerable points. At 5ct and 12mm × 9mm, the corners sit further from the center of the ring than at smaller sizes, increasing daily exposure. On natural stones at $121,000+, ask specifically about corner condition — chips to the corners of a step-cut stone require significant re-cutting. The bezel setting protects corners better than any prong configuration.

**Fluorescence.** A large flat 12mm table makes fluorescence haze more visible than in any other shape at this size. Strong blue fluorescence in a natural 5ct emerald cut can cause the stone to look hazy or oily in daylight. Request faint or none fluorescence for a natural 5ct. In lab, fluorescence is rare and typically not a factor.

**Video before purchase.** The emerald cut at 5ct is responsive to lighting in ways photographs cannot show. A 360° video under natural and indoor lighting is mandatory before buying at either price level. Studio photography under bright ring lights makes every stone look good — real lighting shows the actual optical character of the stone and will reveal any clarity issues the certificate notes do not flag.

